<http2_smuggling_guide>
<title>HTTP/2 SMUGGLING</title>

<critical>HTTP/2 smuggling exploits protocol translation flaws between HTTP/2 frontends and HTTP/1.1 backends. Focus on H2.CL, H2.TE desync attacks, HPACK header compression abuse, pseudo-header injection, and stream multiplexing vulnerabilities. These enable request routing bypass, cache poisoning, and backend access control circumvention.</critical>

<scope>
- H2.CL (HTTP/2 to Content-Length) desynchronization
- H2.TE (HTTP/2 to Transfer-Encoding) desynchronization
- HPACK header compression exploitation
- Stream multiplexing attacks and interference
- Pseudo-header injection (:method, :path, :authority, :scheme)
- HTTP/2 downgrade attacks
- Connection coalescing abuse
- Request tunnel smuggling
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Identify HTTP/2 frontend with HTTP/1.1 backend (common in CDNs, load balancers, proxies)
2. Test protocol translation: send conflicting length indicators (Content-Length + chunked)
3. Probe HPACK compression: inject long headers to manipulate compression tables
4. Test pseudo-headers: inject :method, :path overrides in regular headers
5. Exploit stream multiplexing: send interleaved frames to confuse routing
6. Attempt downgrade: force HTTP/2 to HTTP/1.1 translation errors
7. Validate with timing-based detection and response observation
</methodology>

<attack_types>
<h2_cl_desync>
- HTTP/2 request with Content-Length conflicts:
  Frontend: HTTP/2 frame-based body length
  Backend: HTTP/1.1 Content-Length header
- Frontend uses frame length, backend uses Content-Length
- Payload:
  POST / HTTP/2
  Content-Length: 0
  
  <frame data: "GET /admin HTTP/1.1\r\nHost: backend\r\n\r\n">
- Backend sees Content-Length: 0 but receives body, desync occurs
- Next request on connection is prefixed with smuggled data
</h2_cl_desync>

<h2_te_desync>
- HTTP/2 with Transfer-Encoding in translation:
  POST / HTTP/2
  Transfer-Encoding: chunked
  
  0
  
  GET /admin HTTP/1.1
  Host: backend
- HTTP/2 spec forbids Transfer-Encoding, but proxies may translate to chunked
- Backend interprets chunked encoding, smuggles additional request
</h2_te_desync>

<pseudo_header_injection>
- Inject pseudo-headers as regular headers:
  POST /api/user HTTP/2
  :method: GET
  method: POST
  :path: /api/user
  path: /api/admin
- Frontend honors pseudo-headers (:method, :path)
- Backend may process regular headers if translation is naive
- Result: frontend routes to /api/user, backend executes /api/admin
</pseudo_header_injection>

<header_name_collision>
- HTTP/2 allows any header, HTTP/1.1 has restrictions
- Inject headers with \r\n, \0, or spaces:
  POST / HTTP/2
  X-Forwarded-For: evil\r\nHost: internal.local
- Backend parser may treat injected CRLF as new header line
- Smuggle Host header to redirect to internal targets
</header_name_collision>
</attack_types>

<hpack_exploitation>
<compression_table_manipulation>
- HPACK uses dynamic table for header compression
- Send large uncommon headers to evict common entries
- Force re-transmission of sensitive headers in plain
- Timing side-channel: compressed vs uncompressed response times
</compression_table_manipulation>

<header_bomb>
- Huffman encoding allows compression bomb:
  Encoded small, decodes to massive header
- Cause DoS or buffer overflow in HTTP/1.1 translator
- Payload: compressed to 100 bytes, expands to 10MB
</header_bomb>

<dynamic_table_poisoning>
- Pollute HPACK dynamic table with attacker-controlled headers
- Subsequent requests reuse polluted table entries
- Leak sensitive data via compression oracle
</dynamic_table_poisoning>
</hpack_exploitation>

<stream_multiplexing>
<request_interference>
- Send multiple requests on same connection (streams)
- Reuse stream IDs to interfere with routing
- Payload:
  Stream 1: GET /api/user
  Stream 3: GET /api/admin
  Stream 1: (reuse) GET /api/steal-response
- Backend may route Stream 1 responses to Stream 3
</request_interference>

<response_queue_poisoning>
- Send rapid requests to desync response queue
- Frontend expects response A, receives response B
- Steal other users' responses via queue confusion
</response_queue_poisoning>

<stream_priority_abuse>
- Manipulate stream priority to affect processing order
- Low priority streams may bypass rate limits
- Exhaust stream limits to DoS connection
</stream_priority_abuse>
</stream_multiplexing>

<downgrade_attacks>
<forced_http1_translation>
- Send invalid HTTP/2 that forces fallback to HTTP/1.1
- Protocol error triggers downgrade with smuggled payload
- Payload survives downgrade and executes on backend
</forced_http1_translation>

<alpn_negotiation_bypass>
- Manipulate ALPN to force HTTP/1.1
- Frontend thinks HTTP/2, backend receives HTTP/1.1
- Smuggle in translation layer
</alpn_negotiation_bypass>
</downgrade_attacks>

<detection_techniques>
<timing_based>
- Send request with potential desync payload
- Measure time to first byte for next request
- Desync: next request delayed (processing smuggled request first)
- Send GET / with smuggled POST /slowendpoint
- Normal: ~100ms response
- Desync: ~5000ms response (backend processing smuggled POST first)
</timing_based>

<response_observation>
- Send request with smuggled GET /admin
- Check if response contains admin content
- Differential response: status 200 vs 403, different content length
- Response headers from smuggled request leak into main response
</response_observation>

<connection_state>
- Send desync attempt with unique markers
- Issue normal request on same connection
- Check if response contains markers from smuggled request
- Connection poisoning: subsequent requests affected
</connection_state>
</detection_techniques>

<exploitation_payloads>
<basic_h2_cl>
POST / HTTP/2
Host: target.com
Content-Length: 6

0

GET /admin HTTP/1.1
Host: target.com
Foo: bar
</basic_h2_cl>

<pseudo_header_override>
POST /api/user HTTP/2
Host: target.com
:path: /api/user
X-Override-Path: /api/admin

{"user": "victim"}
</pseudo_header_override>

<header_injection_via_h2>
GET / HTTP/2
Host: target.com
X-Forwarded-For: 127.0.0.1\r\nX-Real-IP: 127.0.0.1

(Backend sees multiple injected headers)
</header_injection_via_h2>

<request_smuggling_template>
POST / HTTP/2
Host: target.com
Content-Length: 150

<DATA FRAME 1: smuggled request start>
GET /admin HTTP/1.1
Host: backend-internal.local
X-Smuggled: true

<DATA FRAME 2: smuggled request continuation>
</request_smuggling_template>
</exploitation_payloads>

<target_environments>
<cdn_configurations>
- Cloudflare, Fastly, Akamai with HTTP/2 frontend
- CDN terminates HTTP/2, translates to HTTP/1.1 for origin
- Edge node -> Origin translation point
</cdn_configurations>

<load_balancers>
- nginx, HAProxy, F5, AWS ALB with HTTP/2 enabled
- LB accepts HTTP/2, forwards HTTP/1.1 to backends
- Protocol translation in reverse proxy
</load_balancers>

<api_gateways>
- Kong, AWS API Gateway, Azure API Management
- API gateway HTTP/2 termination + HTTP/1.1 backend
- Gateway-to-service communication
</api_gateways>

<web_application_firewalls>
- WAF inspects HTTP/2, forwards HTTP/1.1
- Desync bypasses WAF inspection
- Smuggled request not inspected by WAF rules
</web_application_firewalls>
</target_environments>

<impact_scenarios>
<cache_poisoning>
- Smuggle request to poison CDN cache
- Subsequent users receive attacker-controlled content
- Payload: smuggle request with malicious response directive
</cache_poisoning>

<request_routing_bypass>
- Frontend routes based on :path
- Smuggle different path to backend
- Access admin endpoints via routing confusion
</request_routing_bypass>

<credential_hijacking>
- Smuggle request to steal other users' responses
- Capture session tokens, API keys from response queue
- Connection sharing enables cross-user data leakage
</credential_hijacking>

<waf_bypass>
- WAF inspects on frontend (HTTP/2)
- Smuggled payload in HTTP/1.1 translation bypasses inspection
- Execute blocked payloads via protocol desync
</waf_bypass>
</impact_scenarios>

<validation>
1. Prove protocol translation: confirm HTTP/2 frontend with HTTP/1.1 backend
2. Demonstrate desync: timing anomaly or response from smuggled request
3. Show impact: access restricted endpoint, poison cache, or steal response
4. Reproduce reliably: provide exact frames/headers that cause desync
5. Validate connection state: show effect persists across requests on same connection
6. Differential test: compare normal request vs desync request timing/responses
</validation>

<false_positives>
- HTTP/2 errors causing connection reset (not desync)
- Timeouts from network latency (not smuggled request processing)
- Load balancer health check requests interfering with timing
- Backend properly handles HTTP/2 end-to-end (no translation)
- Strict protocol validation preventing desync
</false_positives>

<impact>
- Request routing bypass (access control circumvention)
- Cache poisoning (persistent XSS, content manipulation)
- Credential theft (response queue hijacking)
- WAF/security control bypass
- Internal network access via header injection
- Cross-user data leakage via connection sharing
</impact>

<pro_tips>
1. Look for h2 in Server header or ALPN negotiation to confirm HTTP/2
2. Test CDN origins—most CDNs use HTTP/2 frontend + HTTP/1.1 backend
3. Send requests on same connection to test persistence
4. Use curl --http2 or custom H2 client for precise frame control
5. Timing is key: desync introduces measurable delays in next request
6. Test pseudo-header injection first—easiest to detect and exploit
7. HPACK compression is complex—focus on simpler H2.CL/H2.TE first
8. Connection coalescing (same IP/cert) enables cross-origin attacks
9. Monitor for protocol downgrade events—may indicate vulnerability
10. Test with both GET and POST—different code paths may behave differently
11. Check for duplicate header handling—HTTP/2 allows, HTTP/1.1 varies
12. Validate on multiple endpoints—desync may be endpoint-specific
</pro_tips>

<remember>HTTP/2 smuggling requires protocol translation. Prevent by using HTTP/2 end-to-end, validating Content-Length consistency, rejecting pseudo-headers in regular header positions, and properly handling stream multiplexing. Never trust header values across protocol boundaries.</remember>
</http2_smuggling_guide>
